| Geopolitical Tensions          | Instability in key oil-producing regions                                                        | Supply disruptions, risk premium      |
| Market Speculation             | Financial market activity and shortage psychology                                                | Amplified price volatility             |
| Inflation                     | Rising overall consumer prices and energy costs                                                 | Broader upward pressure on prices     |

---

## 6. Outlook and Conclusion

Analysts are divided on whether high gas prices will persist. Some, like Richard Gorry of JBC Energy Asia, foresee recurring energy crises over the next few years due to limited new natural gas supply and geopolitical uncertainties ([CNBC, 2021](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/10/28/energy-crisis-analysts-split-on-whether-gas-prices-will-remain-high.html)). Others expect supply to catch up by 2025, potentially easing prices ([S&P Global Platts Analytics, 2022](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sp-global-platts-analytics-releases-its-2022-energy-outlook-301443067.html)).

In conclusion, the recent jump in gas prices is primarily attributable to a combination of constrained supply—both from OPEC+ production decisions and reduced U.S. refinery capacity—and a strong rebound in demand as economies reopened post-pandemic. This has been compounded by geopolitical tensions, market speculation, and inflationary pressures. Weather-driven demand fluctuations have further exacerbated the situation. The interplay of these factors has created a "perfect storm" for elevated gas prices, with significant economic consequences including inflation and potential stagflation risks.

